{"componentChunkName":"component---src-page-post-tsx","path":"/principle/five-whys","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Markus Tacker","tagLine":"Software Crafter","description":"Software Crafter building üå©Ô∏è cloud-based cellular IoT solutions at Nordic Semiconductor.‚Äã\n\t\tMentor. Speaker. ‚ÄãConference & Community builder. Camper. üèïÔ∏è üöê","gitHubUrl":"https://github.com/coderbyheart/coderbyheart.com.git","siteUrl":"https://coderbyheart.com","twitter":"@coderbyheart","defaultCard":"https://images.ctfassets.net/bncv3c2gt878/3Jk4P6nFPNzaz1gsguktk8/350b7e4ddb2c7d86416243d9902920e2/social-card-default-2020.png"}}},"pageContext":{"page":{"id":"708e1575-60ac-53bf-81a7-b49661ba4760","name":"five-whys","relativeDirectory":"post/principle","relativePath":"post/principle/five-whys.md","remark":{"htmlAst":{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"properties":{"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/bncv3c2gt878/5EDMlev20tZ1kW0zTINSwR/a4a0556c9013bd32959aada52f5a7a93/snowflake-5-whys.svg?w=1251&h=1083","alt":"Snowflake: 5 whys"},"children":[],"tagName":"img","type":"element"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://coderbyheart.github.io/snowflake/#98:209,276:160,420:124","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"I have a theory that the truth is never told during the nine-to-five hours."},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n‚Äî "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Hunter S. Thompson"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"}],"tagName":"blockquote","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"5 whys"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" method is one of my favorite methods because it is so simple to\nremember and almost naturally to apply in many situations. Whenever you are\npresented with a "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"fact"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" (about a task to implement, a bug, or a problem) use\nthis method to uncover the "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"true"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" origin of this fact."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Given a problem, you ask \"Why ... did this happen?\", the answer you will find or\nbe given is not to be taken at face value at first. Instead this cause should be\nfurther analyzed. This process is repeated "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"at least five times"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":", only then can\nyou be sure to be on track of finding the true cause for the problem."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Of course, the number 5, is arbitrarily picked, and can be any number. The point\nis to be aware that humans have a bias for making assumptions and giving answers\nthat follow these assumptions and thereby follow a false path of conclusion.\nThis ability for quick decision making, using heuristics, has served humans for\na long time, because it yields a higher chance of survival. Daniel Kahneman\ncalls this "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"System 1"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" in his book "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Thinking, Fast and Slow"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"5 whys"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" method is a deliberate process to break out of this simplified\nthought process and engage in true problem analysis (using "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"System 2"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" thinking)."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"It can be visualized using this flow chart:"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"properties":{"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/bncv3c2gt878/5T0iauuV1mnsfWtT7IdIlA/bc59ae8849ce7c10df34aa5983c82397/five-whys-flowchart.svg?w=364&h=605","alt":"5 whys"},"children":[],"tagName":"img","type":"element"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"root cause"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" can be reached immediately after the first question, or require\nmore than 5 iterations. What's needed is the persistence to ask the right\nquestions, and here a great helper is to identify omissions and assumptions that\nwere made when identifying the cause."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Assumptions are rather straightforward to identify, they are usually known and\ncan be uncovered through discussing which assumptions were made when identifying\nthe cause."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Problem: "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The car does not start"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Why did this happen: "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The starter does not work"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Cause: "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The battery is dead"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"}],"tagName":"ul","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The assumption in this analysis is that the dead battery does not supply power\nto the starter."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Omissions are harder to identify, but they are relevant when applying this\ntechnique in a discussion with another person. I especially love this part, and\nI use it regularly in interviews, or when discussing problems with colleagues or\npartners. Here you need to get creative to uncover information that was not\ngiven when providing a cause. The important part here is to keep it a discussion\non eye-level, a problem-focused discovery, not a way to shift responsibility\naway from you. You yourself are responsible for helping to uncover the root\ncause of the problem. The "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"5 why"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" method therefore is also a tool for\nself-reflection and will help to discover your own assumptions, omissions and\ncontributions to a problem's root cause."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"The "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"5 whys"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" method is so powerful because of its simplicity ... but be careful\nnot to come across as annoying when applying it. Showing persistence in\nuncovering fundamental truths takes practice, but always delivers."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#literature","ariaLabel":"literature permalink","className":["anchor","before"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Literature"}],"tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"literature","style":"position:relative;"},"type":"element